  "text": "Before infusions (3-5 days), the pigs were fasted overnight, and the jugular vein and carotid artery of each pig were catheterized using sterile techniques under general anesthesia (Aerrane; Anaquest, Madison, WI) as described previously [CITATION_1] . After surgery, pigs were returned to their cages and resumed their regular treatment regimen. Pancreatic glucose-amino acid clamps. Diluent and pST-treated pigs were fasted overnight (16 h) before the infusion studies. On the day of infusion, pigs were administered their daily dose of pST (180 g/kg body wt) or diluent 60 min before infusion. Clamps were performed using techniques similar to those previously described [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] (Fig. 1) . Over a 30-min period before the initiation of the clamp, basal blood glucose (YSI 2300 STAT Plus; Yellow Springs Instruments, Yellow Springs, OH) and branched-chain amino acid (BCAA) concentrations were determined to establish the average fasting concentration to be used in the glucose-amino acid clamp procedure (54).",
